title: For Sale/Trade:  Gen 3 Night Vision Monocular
postcontent:
I have a gen 3 night vision device with an integral IR laser.  It is a rather uncommon piece known as the MANTIS 140 XLR.  It is comparable to the PVS-14 but the IR laser is 100 mw which is extremely powerful.  The laser has an adjustable focus, but the threads are a little gummed up so it sticks before it focuses all the way back to the laser point, but I have decided not to worry about cleaning the threads simply because an IR laser of that power can be a little dangerous.  Instead it makes a fantastic IR illumination device that can light up a hill side several hundred yards away.  When focused, the laser is supposed to be visible out to 10 kilometers.

The monocular has in integral weapons mount and mounts right behind my IR capable EOTech, however, I have never actually fired the gun with it mounted in this fashion.  Instead I just use it handheld.  When the laser can be focused down it is actually adjustable for point of aim, however, to use it effectively in this manner it would take a pressure switch that is rather hard to come by.

The price is meant to reflect the going rate for a PVS-14 plus a mil-spec 100 mw IR laser, however, that is just a starting point.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Pulsar N550 Digiscope
postcontent:
This is a listing for a Pulsar N550 digital night scope.  If you are looking for this, you probably know what it is, but just in case here is a brief explanation.  Basically, instead of using special photo sensitive films it uses a chip like a digital camera and enhances the picture to allow you to see in the dark.  The big benefit that this provides is the ability to be used during the day without damaging anything.  It also has some other features that make it pretty entertaining like the fact that it has a video out so you can record your night hunts.  Just check youtube for hog hunts and you will see what I mean.  It also has a nifty feature called one-shot-zero.  Basically, it allows you to zero it on your rifle with a single shot.  Simply mount it to the rifle, aim at a single point and take a shot.  Next, activate the zero function and while holding the cross hairs on the initial point of aim you use the buttons to move a floating x over the point of impact and voila!  Your scope is now zeroed after a single shot.  This also means that if you record how far off mechanical zero each of your rifles is, you can transfer it between them and just adjust accordingly, so one shot from each rifle and you can swap out at will.

This has the original bag and accessories, to include the video out cables, so is ready to record your hunt as soon as you get it!

title: For Trade:  Good Advice for Sellers
location: Statewide, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Please include a fair market price. Listings that state $1 means that there will be haggling involved and realistically there will be many low ball offers for you to sift through. Putting a price on your listing at least let's people know what you expect even if you are willing to negotiate. People come on Armslist expect to barter some but stay reasonable in expectations.

Second, check your grammar. This is not English class but if you use "whatcha got" and other cute phrases like that you send a very non-professional message and honestly I would prefer to do business with a more professional seller.

This is not meant to be rude or condescending but rather some friendly advice to help you generate more sales and keep Armslist as professional as possible.

Wishing you the best Armslist experience possible.

You can flag this if you want, and you probably will, but it is still good advice and will help you sell more items in the long run. If you agree with what I have said and it makes sense, then please let it stay up for others to learn from. 

Thank you and Merry Christmas!

title: For Sale:  Inglis Browning Hi-Power
location: West of Berthoud, Fort Collins, Colorado
postcontent:
Browning Hi-Power Made by Inglis in Canada 1943-1945

For sale is what you see in the picture which is a Browing Hi-Power (aka P-35) made under contract from Fabrique Nationale, Belgium by John Inglis in Canada, a reproduction board shoulder stock and a 1953 Canadian holster, lanyard and two clips.  Inglis reportedly (The Browning Hi-Power Automatic Pistol book) made 151,816 of these in the Mark I and Mark II patterns.  Approximately 50,000 Mark 1's as this is, were made under what is called the Chinese contract, however few if any went to the Chinese because of WWII demand for side arms.  The Mark I's are differentiated from the Mark II's by the slotted grip to accept a shoulder stock and the adjustable tangent sight versus the driftable only blade sight.  The Mark I's are said to be in the most demand.  You should understand that ATFE says that only the original stock that looks like the ones used with C-96 Mauser (aka broomhandle) is legal to attach to the pistol.  All reproductions are not.

I think my Chinese contract Inglis (it has CH in the serial number) has been refinished by the seller, Pacific International (their ad said “absolutely original and unaltered,” but didn't say not refinished) because my readings indicate that they were finished in a black lacquer (carcinogenic by the way) or parkerized and mine looks blued and parkerized.  And I see buffing lines on the slide with the Mark I * is gone except for the asterisk (*).  Bore is shiny and good and the serial number is on all the parts (aka matching serial numbers) The original clip has the II that looks like a T with two legs indicating its original and the other is aftermarket I bought.  Due to the pixel limit I can send you all the pix you want if interested.

title: For Sale:  Kimber Compact Stainless Series I, Galco leather, lots of extras.
postcontent: This is not your average Kimber. These were made for a short time, it is an officers size frame with a commander length slide. Here is a gun with all the attention to details of a Wilson Combat but at half the price. It has been polished to a high shine along the side of the slide as well as the thumb safe, slide release, magazine release, and through pins. The rest is a matte silver bead blast texture. This is an early Kimber series I, before the external extractors and cheapened internals that have sadly become standard in the more mass produced Kimbers. This is an all Stainless gun, no aluminum alloy frame. It has the Kimber low profile sights, they have been perfectly adjusted, by drifting and milling, for elevation and windage at 20 yards. The original plastic mainspring housing has been replaced with a stainless Wilson Combat 20 LPI housing. The Grip safety has been fitted with an Ed Brown memory grip beavertail safety, precision installed and mounted to allow your hand to grip as high as possible to the bore centerline. The thumb safe is also an Ed Brown, it is an extended tactical safety that angles slightly downward to allow more ergonomic handling. The trigger is a Kimber match grade with adjustable overtravel screw. The guide rod bushing is new in the last 200 rounds, as is the recoil spring. I have a new pack of 3 recoil springs and the original guide rod bushing as replacements too. Grips are Kimber custom green laminate with diamond checkering. Trigger is set to break clean at 3.5 pounds, very little creep or overtravel. This is a very light trigger and may surprise even a trained 1911 shooter, but it can be easily brought back to 5 or so pounds by replacing the sear spring at about $4 from Midway. Galco carry holster is practically unused, the outside waist band holster is in good shape and well worn in, the magazine pouch is also in great shape, all leather is Galco. It comes with the take down tool, users manual, original plastic box, as well as the shammy and embroidered Kimber gray carry case which fits the gun and a magazine perfectly. Absolutely beautiful gun, as aesthetically attractive as it is functional. Give me a call or email if interested, text doesn't work. Thanks.
